    excerpt: 'The Rosary is often dismissed as mere repetition — and yet repetition, rightly understood, is the very structure of contemplative prayer.',
    body: `<p>The Rosary is often dismissed as mere repetition — and yet repetition, rightly understood, is the very structure of contemplative prayer. The Jesus Prayer of the Eastern tradition, the liturgical chanting of the Divine Office, the recitation of the Psalms: each employs repetition not to lull the mind to sleep, but to free it from the noise of its own chatter so that the heart may attend to God.</p>
    <p>St. John Paul II, in his apostolic letter <em>Rosarium Virginis Mariae</em>, described the Rosary as "a compendium of the Gospel." Each mystery is a window into the life of Christ — seen, as it were, through the eyes of His mother. We do not merely recall events; we are invited to dwell within them, to let them speak to our own experience of grace, struggle, and hope.</p>
    <p>There is a pedagogy here that rewards patience. The beginner recites; the intermediate meditates; the advanced contemplates. These are not stages to be rushed through but depths to be sounded. The same mysteries that first seemed familiar gradually reveal themselves as inexhaustible. The Annunciation is always new. The Resurrection always surprises.</p>
    <p>Pick up the beads, then, not as a religious exercise to be completed, but as a school to be attended. Let Our Lady teach you to look at her Son.</p>`
