    title: 'The Real Presence: What Faith Asks of the Mind',
    date: 'March 2025',
    excerpt: 'The doctrine of the Real Presence is among the hardest things Christianity asks us to believe. It is also, perhaps, the most important.',
    body: `<p>The doctrine of the Real Presence is among the hardest things Christianity asks us to believe. It is also, perhaps, the most important. At every Mass, the Church claims that bread and wine become, truly and substantially, the Body and Blood, Soul and Divinity of Jesus Christ. Not symbolically. Not figuratively. Actually.</p>
    <p>This claim scandalized many of Our Lord's disciples in the sixth chapter of John's Gospel, and it scandalizes many still. "This is a hard saying; who can listen to it?" Yet Jesus, far from softening the claim when the crowds grew restless, intensified it: "Unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink his blood, you have no life in you."</p>
    <p>St. Thomas Aquinas gave us the philosophical vocabulary — transubstantiation — to articulate how this can be so. The substance of bread changes while the accidents remain. It is not a contradiction but a miracle: a transformation beneath the surface of things that our senses cannot detect and our reason cannot fully comprehend.</p>
    <p>What faith asks of the mind, in the end, is not the suspension of reason but its humble extension. We are asked to believe that the One who spoke the universe into being can speak bread into His own Body. Given who He is, the real question is not whether this is possible — but whether we are willing to receive it.</p>`
