    excerpt: 'To understand Maximilian Kolbe, one must understand his conviction that the Immaculate Conception is not simply a privilege of Mary but a weapon against Satan.',
    body: `<p>To understand Maximilian Kolbe, one must understand his conviction that the Immaculate Conception is not simply a privilege of Mary but a weapon against Satan — the ultimate expression of divine grace triumphing over sin and pride. From this conviction, the Militia Immaculata was born: a movement of souls consecrated to Our Lady for the conversion of sinners and the renewal of the world.</p>
    <p>Kolbe was a Franciscan friar, a publisher, a missionary to Japan, and finally a martyr at Auschwitz — where he voluntarily took the place of a condemned man in the starvation bunker. These are not unrelated facts but expressions of a single vision: that love, when fully surrendered to God through Mary, becomes capable of anything.</p>
    <p>His theology of Mary was Trinitarian at its root. Mary's Immaculate Conception makes her the perfect spouse of the Holy Spirit — the uncreated Love between Father and Son. In consecrating ourselves to her, Kolbe believed, we are drawn into this Trinitarian exchange and transformed by it. We become, in a real sense, instruments of the Spirit's action in the world.</p>
    <p>What would it mean to take this seriously? Not as piety, but as vocation? Kolbe's life suggests that it would mean exactly what he lived: a total surrender of self, a radical availability to grace, and a love willing to walk into the darkness without flinching.</p>`
