    excerpt: 'There is a Catholic way of reading Scripture, and it is not the way most people — including many Catholics — have been taught.',
    body: `<p>There is a Catholic way of reading Scripture, and it is not the way most people — including many Catholics — have been taught. The dominant modern approach, absorbed from the culture, treats Scripture like any other ancient text: a document to be analyzed, historically situated, and decoded by trained specialists. This is useful, as far as it goes. But it is not enough.</p>
    <p>The Church reads Scripture from within the living Tradition that produced it. The Bible is not a library of independent books but a unified narrative — what the Catechism calls "one book" whose author is ultimately the Holy Spirit. To read it well, one must read it in and with the Church, attentive to the fourfold sense: literal, allegorical, moral, and anagogical.</p>
    <p>The allegorical sense, in particular, has become foreign to modern readers. But it was instinctive to the Fathers. For Origen, for Augustine, for Gregory the Great, every page of the Old Testament was transparent to Christ. The Exodus prefigured Baptism; the manna in the desert prefigured the Eucharist; the Song of Songs prefigured the soul's union with God. This was not fanciful allegory but the perception of a typological depth built into history itself by its divine Author.</p>
    <p>To recover this reading is to discover that the Scriptures are not merely about the past but about us — about the journey every soul makes from slavery to freedom, from darkness to light, from death to the life that God alone can give.</p>`
