    body: `<p>"Lord Jesus Christ, Son of God, have mercy on me, a sinner." Twelve words. Yet in the Christian East, these twelve words became the foundation of an entire school of prayer — the Hesychast tradition, which sought nothing less than the transformation of the entire person through unceasing invocation of the Holy Name.</p>
    <p>The prayer rope — the chotki or komboskini — is its companion: a simple cord of knots used to count repetitions and anchor the wandering mind. For the Eastern Christian, the prayer rope is what the Rosary beads are for the Western Catholic: not a magical object but a physical tether, a reminder that prayer engages the body as well as the soul.</p>
    <p>Catholics who discover this tradition often feel they have come home to something they did not know they were missing. The Jesus Prayer is not foreign to the Catholic spirit — its Christology is impeccably orthodox, its spirituality entirely consonant with the Latin tradition of affective prayer. St. Gregory Palamas and St. John of the Cross, writing from different lungs of the Church, breathe the same air.</p>
    <p>To hold the prayer rope and pray the Jesus Prayer is to join a river of intercession that has flowed for fifteen centuries — from the desert fathers of Egypt to the monks of Mount Athos to Christians praying in their kitchens today. It is to discover that the Catholic tradition is wider and deeper than we imagined, and that the Holy Spirit has been at work everywhere.</p>`
